European inflation slipped into food
Accelerated inflation in the euro area is primarily due to the breakneck growth in food prices.
The increase in prices in the month of November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Statistical Office of the Union based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts only gave 3 percent as likely, Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut basic interest rates, on the pretext that the decline, together with rising commodity prices and reduced forced unemployment, would spiral inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "you have to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene in this issue later.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the twelve-year record; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of soaring food and energy prices.
Forward quotations for wheat increased by 88 percent and soybean prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent, while by 2009 it will already fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 percent in the next 3 or 4 months, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice in 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stalemate, by early December support for the Alliance of Young Democrats increased significantly, reaching its highest level since 2002, while Gallup has never before experienced such a low level – 13 percent – in the case of the Socialists.
The difference in the case of secure party voters - due to the firmer strength of opposition voters - would mean more than two-thirds support (71 percent) compared to one-fifth support for the Socialists (20 percent).
According to the poll, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach even the necessary limit to have any parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous low point - it has never been higher, with 41 percent of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the more hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as the next year is concerned, the majority of the population is counting on the deterioration of the situation and only a tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those consulted, a figure higher than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the President of the Government rather performs his functions badly than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány a lot, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of those consulted.
54 percent of the population does not trust the Head of Government at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced vis-à-vis the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 per cent felt that it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, this proportion is currently only 20 per cent, while the relative majority (33 per cent) believe that the only solution is the holding of new elections.
The interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the question about participation answered that they would surely participate and another 20 percent said they are likely to participate.
By way of comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" only 55 percent of the population would surely participate and another 15 percent believe their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters, there is no doubt about the outcome of the referendum.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of study fees, 79 percent of medical consultations and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters would reject the introduction of study fees, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The hypermarkets of the Budaörs gold trading triangle maintained the average price level increase of 16 percent, with the difference that VAT has not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the gold trading triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the newspaper Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth well above one thousand HUF.
As in December of last year prices in food supermarkets had already "skyrocketed", so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below nine thousand HUF, today they cannot do even for ten thousand.
Napi's basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded with a minimum of 91 HUF the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was equally surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with a two-litre redeemable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in the basket of Napi Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to last year's Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15 percent, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent the prices listed in Napi's basket.
Comparing the values of the most expensive basket of last year with that of the cheapest basket of this year, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between the cheapest of last year and the most expensive of this year has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was HUF 1206, so that during Christmas last year prices felt the VAT increase.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of price changes on consumption.
(If the merchant plans poorly the speed of a product's circulation, he may lose a significant profit on the margin that adjusts to the volume of sales.)
The increase in the price of Napi's basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was higher with HUF 1720 than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only HUF 844.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of basic consumer items grew more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some staple foods, registered in the interval of 12 months a price increase of more than 30 percent.
For example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of eggs.)
According to Napi's basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive and last year compared to the base, it was registered, in the worst case only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic increase in prices even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking the preserved food by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed in front of the checkouts at all three stores because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the income is below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals, caused primarily by the improper application of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, overcrowded beds and overloaded staff are not conducive to infection control, says the physician-head of department at the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals you save even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a contagion with MRSA has been diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient shortly after had to return to the hospital as a result of the contagion with MRSA and since then it has not been possible to perform a major surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multiresistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, medical department head of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that hospitals have certainly recorded this number of infections caused by multiresistant agents, the rest there is no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g., throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once overapplied or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics transform into highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and spread quickly in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicaemia primarily in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with weakened organism, the elderly or underweight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the Hospital János there is nothing special about the infection of MRSA, these infections are daily in hospitals.
Infection should not be confused with epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
"These patients are isolated, the nurses care for them in rubber gloves and masks and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are pre-screened for MRSA in their body, but even then infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances are not conducive to the prevention of formation and contagion with multiresistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Because this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should screen hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient - said the doctor-head of department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict mandates for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
It is necessary to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, that is, microbiological tests should be done to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent in the case of outpatients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through healthcare workers.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but also in this regard considerable shortages are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is spread through droplet transmission and direct person-to-person contact, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
What's more, hospital wards are often crowded, beds are often close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals with a less favorable economic situation you save with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where adequate prevention measures are adhered to, fewer infections of this type are registered or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
Treating the spread of infection with MRSA is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is being fought in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, infections with MRSA show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multiresistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
Negative breathalyzer test of the police commander who caused a fatal accident
The official expert report has been made on the case of the fatal accident caused by the commander of the police of the XXII district.
It can be excluded the possibility that the since then resigned commander of the XXII district police, who on Tuesday ran over and caused the death of a passer-by - Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Attorney General's Office of the Capital, said on Friday after the expert report on the case had been prepared.
The expert report confirmed the result of the primary breathalyzer test that had already found that the former police commander did not consume alcoholic beverage before getting behind the wheel.
The then chief of the police station of the XXII district, on Tuesday with his private vehicle when turning to Kossuth Lajos Street in District XXII ran over a 55-year-old man, who intended to cross the street, but not in the area designated for pedestrians.
(This last fact, that is, that the pedestrian did not use the zebra to cross the street, according to the regulations of the Traffic Code are not extenuating circumstances, the driver must always yield the right of way when turning.)
The passerby lost his life after being hospitalized.
Because of what happened, the district police leader resigned and requested his retirement, according to the police statement, because he was very moved by the case.
The investigation of the case is being conducted by the Budapest Investigative Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also said that the former police commander from the beginning collaborated with the prosecutors in charge of the investigation.
€400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian Finance Minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice-President Marta Gajecka signed three credit cap agreements worth a total of 400 million euros in Budapest on Friday to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget transport and environmental protection projects, to be carried out from the cohesion fund grant, for which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million,  The contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The €150 million loan agreement is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this objective of Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million the decision will be taken later, when extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the innovations and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the construction of the 4th Metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary finalizes with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will return to the issue of whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do it.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth €8.4 billion.
The interest on the loans is adjusted to the EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging a fee for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
Bulgaria, the EU's real estate haven
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is admirable - the attention of all Europe is directed towards that Balkan country mentioned above.
What, where and who buys on the even cheaper EU market, which will quickly become more expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
The preferred target for real estate acquisitions in Eastern Europe is undoubtedly Bulgaria, with its cheap ski apartments and beach chalets.
The mountainous regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are the most preferred, while on the beaches Albena, the "Costa Dorada", the "Costa del Sol", the old Sozopol and Nesebar, but more and more people are looking for real estate also around Kavarna and Balchik.
According to analysts of Re/Max in Bulgaria, sooner or later also the central area of the country - such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna - will arouse the interest of real estate developers and more and more people will buy real estate in the especially cheap area of Rus.
In the same way, the capital Sofia can be attractive, the commercial and office spaces promise a rapid return on investment.
Bulgaria is on the best way to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe, thus being a prominent destination also during the other two seasons, in addition to summer and winter.
Therefore, cautious investors are already making their purchases, for example in the vicinity of Bansko.
In the opinion of analysts, those who buy real estate in Bulgaria are also striving to change their lives and their way of life.
Most of the customers are English, but they also come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot promoters are also present, and traditionally there are many Russian customers on Black Sea beaches and ski havens.
Foreign customers can be classified into three groups - says Georgi Jankov, regional director of Re/Max in Bulgaria.
Those who intend to settle here buy new or renovated properties for a price between 50 and 100 thousand euros or old houses in poor condition between 5 and 15 thousand euros, to renovate them later.
They demand good communication and access, and for them the proximity of a big city, shops and usually a local doctor is important.
The second category is the buyers of villas (Bulgaria in December was included among the top 10 holiday destinations of the Germans).
The third group is made up of real estate investors who make their purchases with the hope of benefiting in the medium or long term.
The price of the capital's real estate is constantly growing, since the demand is increasing.
Although in the European Union Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices, in the last five years these suffered an annual increase of 21 percent
The increase in the price of real estate considerably exceeds the growth of wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at the expert level will be completed on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration, negotiations at ministerial level on the post-2012 international climate regime will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap on post-emission reduction efforts, established in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
Lively discussions are currently taking place between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that for the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to agree that compared to the situation of 1990, until 2020 the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological aid to countries in need.
Agreement was also reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a board of directors composed of 16 members, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's six percent
On behalf of Hungary, Minister for the Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to preserve its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister declared that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent compared to the 1990 level by 20 percent, regardless of whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed, and is ready to commit to reducing even 30 percent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to take on commitments commensurate with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 percent, within this the then 15 EU member states committed to comply with an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce by 6 percent the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect compared to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will comply with - according to the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali, because in two years' time the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reductions, whose need was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the international scientific association of the UN that deals with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the reduction in emissions and could not prevent an increase of more than 2°C in the average temperature of the Earth, which scientists say would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British army recruits on YouTube
British army units at a video distributor release footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: special units deployed in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - reported the BBC.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general operations corps of Kandahar, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are already 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been uploaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos with recruitment objectives, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the British army's presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs virtually nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots - defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'être of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the suspiciously edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the dealership, for example about the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently seizing this opportunity.
The Americans use a slightly different way of recruiting with the freely downloadable shooter video games called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers.
