Banks want to solve the crisis
The American Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian Central Banks decided to fight together against the crisis of the Finance Market.
In the monetary marking, more than one hundred billion dollars will be received through tenders.
In these tenders the banks auction the interest rates for which they are able to lend money.
For example, the American Fed will send forty billion dollars to tender, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the attacks of September 11, it is the first time that central banks of different states agree on this coordinated process to protect and lessen the consequences of the financial crisis.
"This step must solve the biggest economic problem, namely the continued growth of the shortage of free capital that banks could lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report to clients.
"This coordinated action by central banks likely slowed the recession in the United States from 65 percent to fifty percent," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent sixty billion dollars on unpaid loans, mostly in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
"Central banks must be really afraid of what still awaits them when they decided to take this step," said ABN Amro chief economist Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems of access to loans and that they will therefore have to lend more expensive to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the American economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the world economy.
The central banks thus decided, after they failed to reduce the so-called LIBOR tariff, London's interbank tariff used for the lending of money in the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to lend money even as the central banks of the US, Canada and Britain cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
"It will have the same effect as another drop in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some economists are not surprised that the step taken by central banks contributes to ignite the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem that is the fall of the housing market in the US.
