The place best known to most visitors does not change.
And therefore, it is not necessary to talk more about Havana or Varadero.
Perhaps, just remember that in the aforementioned Hemingway hacienda there is a museum that for those who are lovers of the writer, should not miss it.
The Viñales Valley is the most picturesque corner of Cuba to the west of the island.
Lush vegetation growing on limestone lands.
Mogotes, pylons of limestone rock and rocks of high steep in the falls of the valley, and in its caves fertile lands are acclimatized thanks to which rocks are formed that hide dense vegetation.
The valley is probably where the highest quality tobacco in Cuba is grown.
Visiting one of the Havana cigar factories you can find your final product.
Perhaps someone finds it interesting that the Chilean part of the series, Major Zeman, was filmed there.
Trinity
City of old ancestry that was founded not long after the Spanish colonized the island.
Slavery and sugar brought her fame and wealth.
Wealth turned to beauty with the constructions in the small town.
Spanish colonial architecture, especially influenced by French settlers who arrived later, has hardly changed in four centuries.
Trinidad, between the sea and the Sierra de Escambray, is such a remote place that even in the 50s of the last century there was no road that linked it with the rest of the country.
Such isolation helped her stay out of the rest.
Nothing new was built and therefore, nothing was destroyed, because each person was happy to have a place to live.
If you have more time to be in Trinidad than a single afternoon, it is worth knowing interesting places in the nearby surroundings such as Playa de Ancón or the valley of the sugar factories.
the night belongs to the House of Music, which animates with its music the silence of the mornings.
Baracoa
Small town in the extreme west of Cuba, some consider it to be the most beautiful on the island.
Surely that opinion is already confirmed by the way itself.
The two highways that reach there from Guantánamo must pass through high and broken mountains, as well as through a nature that barely knows the action of man.
