They did not reach an agreement on the future status of the province on Wednesday, during the last session of negotiations in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
The Kosovo Serbs and Albanians ended a sixth and final session of discussions in Baden in Austria on Wednesday morning without being able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on status," European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger told a news conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was " at stake ", his American counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their efforts to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of negotiations.
"We do not foresee violence for now but we enter a very difficult period," he added, noting that " obvious tensions exist ".
End of mediation on 10 December
The mediators of the troika, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will go one last time on Monday in Serbia and Kosovo.
The future of the province populated by 90% Albanians could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko return their relationship to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The discussions in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final session of negotiations since the troika was tasked with a new mediation by the UN last August.
Americans and Europeans believe their mediation will be completed on Dec. 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence in Kosovo in the Security Council, insist on a persecution of negotiations beyond this deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," Botsane-Khartchenko said.
Unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, Westerners consider independence under European Union supervision to be the only viable solution.
Pristina feels prepared to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not rule in her favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been found," announced the president of Kosovo's autonomous authority, Fatmir Sejdiu, at the Baden hotel where these "last chance negotiations" had been held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, has reported his sorrows.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade " belonged to a past that has led to homicides and deportations ".
" Domino Effect "
Serbian President Boris Tadic has considered for his part that a compromise was always feasible, warning the Kosovo Albanian majority against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the province's independence.
Belgrade says it particularly fears a " domino effect " in a region still weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
"For Serbia," he said, "this does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision be exclusively the responsibility of the Security Council, in which its Russian ally has a right of veto.
" The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word "
" Only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia ", Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica had declared.
"These negotiations have lasted two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council. "
To reporters, Fatmir Sedjiu had replied that " the Kosovo Parliament will have the last word on status ", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanians would be made " in concert " with the Westerners.
Bush Starts Israeli-Palestinian Agreement
President George Bush announced, at the opening of the international peace conference he met Tuesday in Annapolis, Maryland, that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed on a joint declaration.
He said Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to immediately enter into negotiations in view of finding a final regulation of the 60-year-old dispute between their two peoples.
In the presence of both men, Bush promised he would do everything to help them conclude a "peace treaty" before the end of 2008.
Meanwhile, the Palestinians must dismantle "terrorist infrastructures" and Israel must end its settlement activities, Bush said, reminding both sides of their obligations regarding the road map for peace they agreed to in 2003.
The White House chief stressed that negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority chaired by Abbas would attempt "to conclude a peace treaty that would resolve all outstanding issues, without exception, including the core issues."
This designation covers the three main thorny issues of the Israeli-Palestinian dispute: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of Arab refugees expelled from their homes during the 1948 conflict.
Taking the floor after the American president, Abbas insisted that the upcoming negotiations be "comprehensive and deepened" and refer to all aspects of a regulation, citing "Jerusalem, refugees, borders, settlements, water, security, among other things."
Returning to the rostrum, Olmert pledged to make the upcoming negotiations "direct and continuous" and to make "an effort to conclude them in the course of 2008."
Bush set the end of 2008 for the end of the implementation of his " vision of two states " Palestinian and Israeli living side by side.
Saudi Arabia revealed that it had secured an effort in this regard from Bush before deciding to participate in the conference.
Saudi Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis is a success for Washington, is at the beginning of a plan, endorsed by all Arab countries, which proposes peace to Israel in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis marks "a point of confrontation in the history of the Middle East, more particularly because it attacks the roots of the conflict and its central aspects," Prince Saoud said in his periodic Arab interview with Saudi capitals.
