A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were hitherto not consultable only for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is to say individually and by name, at the request of a former victim or his successors in title.
The eleven states in charge of managing it - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to seekers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow searches "particularly on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced labourers," explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives run by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, were opposed to the opening to the public of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the countrymen deported or subjected to compulsory work and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Still in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
" There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents, " Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin, had stated in 2006.
