What insurance is right for me?
Car insurance, which covers the driver against possible accidents, involves an important expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, age of the license, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or the use of it, among others.
Having the car is only the beginning.
Choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the vehicle model.
First of all, we must be clear about what we are talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insured.
This commitment is materialized in an insurance contract, which establishes that the company receives the value of the agreed premium in exchange for being responsible for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of an accident.
The premium is the price of the insurance, which is established taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, the age of the license, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use that is given to it, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so that the greater the probability of suffering an accident, the higher the fee to be paid.
It is for this reason that both those over 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, since statistics show that they have a lower accident rate due to their prudence.
Also, using the counts, companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use that is given to the vehicle will influence the frequency, and with it in the probability of having some type of mishap.
Increasing the frequency increases the odds.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when establishing the price of the premium.
That is why the driver must study the situation well to choose the car insurance that best suits his profile.
We will expose here the most significant variables when choosing one or another type of insurance, so that it, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insured, offers a reasonable price.
Young people under 25 years of age encounter various drawbacks when taking out insurance at an affordable price, such as reduced driving experience and the age of the license.
Although the ideal to be well insured is comprehensive insurance, there are other cheaper options.
The most cautious drivers can opt for an all-risk with excess, so that they obtain the coverage of a comprehensive insurance but at a more feasible price.
This type of agreement would mean that the client pays a part of the amount of the claim.
"The part of the amount of the claim contributed by the client will be pre-established based on the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount," specifies Luis Noguera, head in Spain of First Europa, online insurance mediator.
Another option is an extended third-party insurance, so that the client ensures protection against damage caused to third parties, although not against those caused in his own car.
In addition, it would be covered for theft, fire and the loss of the vehicle.
A piece of advice.
If you are under 25 years old, try to be careful and avoid accidents as much as possible, as this will affect the bonus, and may reduce the cost of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction on the base rate that the company has.
Conversely, a penalty is a surcharge on that base rate.
"The bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and its benefit.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to increase bonuses," says Noguera.
After the age of 25, drivers have it easier when it comes to taking out insurance, since the accident rate is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
For this reason, it is best to hire an all-risk franchise.
"Normally young people can not make use of the experience previously acquired when it comes to fending for themselves in an accident, and even when driving," says the director in Spain of the European company, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, once the 'fear of the rookie' has passed.
However, if the client is married but does not yet have children, it is preferable that he negotiate comprehensive insurance, as long as his economic situation allows it, of course.
On the other hand, marriages with children are considered by insurers as the public with the lowest accident rate, so the surcharges will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be a comprehensive one with excess (this can be 300 euros), or, when a high level of bonus is available, one to third parties extended from the third year of life of the vehicle.
"They carry out a more relaxed driving and have a greater purchasing power to afford to assume a greater amount of franchise," says Luis Noguera.
For retirees, it is advisable to have comprehensive insurance with a franchise (this being 150 euros), or an extended third party insurance when there is a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is important, not only because it covers the driver against possible accidents, but also because it represents an important expense, which is why it is essential to properly study the insurance that suits us best according to our personal situation.
