New gas fears between Russia and Ukraine
The growing gas price dispute between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk that it will affect Russia's export of the fuel to Western Europe.
Most of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is routed through Ukraine, so every friction between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher transit fees.
An earlier dispute last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, the monopoly owner of gas, Gazprom, trying to agree on the amount of money Ukraine was to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom said it will charge Ukraine more, which has pledged to pay an extra 50 percent in 2008 for gas coming from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say Ukraine could pay 40% more for Gazprom's imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important transits for gas during the talks," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters news agency.
"Changes in gas prices should not be related to our arguments about the levels of transit charges [to Western Europe] via Ukraine."
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut off supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly raised prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU's supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supply with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet nations in Central Asia.
NHS 'will have to test foreign workers'
The Scottish NHS needs to check the criminal records of employees from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
Auditor General Robert Black's recommendation came after a foreign doctor was found to be linked to the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland has no accurate idea of how many overseas staff it has.
However, his report pointed to other controls that are carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The auditor general checked the number of foreign staff hired outside the European economic area, following the attacks on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at Paisley's Royal Alexandra Hospital, was arrested at the airport after crashing a jeep into the gates of the airport's terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who performed at the Old Bailey via video conference in October, charged in connection with the alleged car bombings in Britain.
NHS expects to carry out pre-employment checks on candidates, to ensure they meet qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK.
Although the Scottish Board of Health uses Disclosure Scotland to carry out criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of Britain.
The auditor general's report recommends, among other measures, that boards should have guidance from the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside Britain.
"Although we found some of the personal records with evidence of these controls, this is not a routine review," the report says.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: "Our report highlights areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available on the number of NHS overseas staff."
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "highly unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
"The report suggests that pre-employment checks work in NHS Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made is," he explained.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign nationals, most of them doctors and nurses
But the auditor general cautioned that the number may be higher, in part because boards have trouble identifying employees with indefinite residency permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures set up by NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being largely complied with.
This includes passport controls, work permit and qualification checks.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing the pre-employment policy and guidance for foreigners on the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was keenly interested in this work being carried out in the wake of the Glasgow airport terror attack.
He added that the Scottish Government, in conjunction with the health boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this will be reflected in the update of the pre-employment control guidelines for all working groups - including overseas - which they planned to publish next month.
