The independent film awards, known as BIFAS, are selected by a team that includes filmmakers, actors and festival organizers.
Bifa festival supporters and patrons include Mike Figgis, Ken Loach, Ewan McGregor, Samantha Morton, Bill Nighy, Meera Syal and Michael Winterbottom.
Saudi Arabia arrests 208 terrorists
Saudi Arabia revealed yesterday that it arrested 208 militants from terrorist cells who were planning an imminent attack on oil facilities, as well as attacks on religious and security forces.
State television from the world's largest oil supplier said one of the cells was planning missile smuggling.
Al-Qaeda sympathizers have mounted a campaign against the local monarchy, in alliance with the United States, since 2003 following the invasion of Iraq.
A cell of eight militants made up of foreign residents was planning an attack on an oil facility in Eastern province, the television report said.
Saudi Arabia created a 35,000-strong force to protect the Abqaiq facility, the world's largest oil plant, after a failed al-Qaeda attack in 2006.
The report, citing a statement by the Saudi Interior Minister, said 18 of those arrested belong to a cell led by a "missile launch expert" that has entered the country.
The minister said the militants had planned to smuggle eight shells into the country.
Another 22 of the detainees were planning assassinations of religious leaders and security forces.
The government warned religious leaders that they must be more active in stopping Saudis traveling to Iraq to join as militants to al-Qaeda to fight allied forces and to back the Shiite Muslim government, which is considered heretical by the most extreme Saudi Sunnis.
Al-Qaeda militants are targeting many clerics in Saudi Arabia who have been appointed by authorities to support the policies of the royal family, which dominates the government.
The militants — recruited by calls from Osama bin Laden, the Saudi-born al-Qaeda leader, to harass the country's pro-Western government — targeted government-associated foreign residences, government buildings and energy facilities.
"This was a great effort by the security forces, for five months of work," the interior minister's spokesman told state television.
Those arrested also include a 16-person "media cell" in Medina, whose aim was to promote "takfiri thinking" — the ideology of radical Sunni Muslims that supports violence against Muslims considered infidels and apostates.
The arrest includes 32 other people accused of providing support and financial support to the militants.
Venus' Climate May Give Insight into Earth's Future
Venus may once have been an appropriate place for life, scientists declared yesterday.
Data from an orbiting European spacecraft showed the planet more like an Earth twin than previously observed.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made Earth habitable, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus into a very different kind of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is enough to melt lead, and it is eroded by hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The results from the European Space Agency for Venus Express, which has studied the planet for a year, offer a glimpse of how Earth could develop catastrophic changes due to climate.
Professor Fred Taylor, from the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from Earth's, when they are two planets so similar.
"Our new data make it possible to build a scenario in which Venus began like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment millions of years ago."
