HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 million charge on its U.S. consumer finance business, in part because of weak card borrowers.
However, it is too early to panic.
Delinquency and crime are at low levels.
According to Moody's, a ratings agency, the third-quarter crime rate of 3.89% was nearly one percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the American bankruptcy law (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy filings, which in turn represent a large loss on credit cards; The number of applications (and therefore, delinquencies) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were getting worse.
The industry also reports strong payment rates, which show how much of its debts consumers pay each month.
And confidence in credit cards and asset-backed securities is fairly firm, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that issuance volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of infection of the crisis between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge credit cards with debt now that lenders are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more at liquidity flow than active securities, so falling prices don't necessarily trigger a shift in borrowers' creditworthiness.
They can even work to outperform issuers.
The incentives for consumers to continue paying off the mortgage decreases if the properties are worth less than the value of the loan; And as a result, paying off card debt goes up the priority list.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to difficult conditions than mortgage lenders by changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That in theory should reduce the risk of a quick asset revaluation.
"We're not going to wake up one day and reassess all the loans," says Gary Perlin, Capital One's chief financial officer.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
