Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that until now had not been raised. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and eddies at the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that there might be lightning on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, lightning strikes from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to Urey-Miller's famous origin-of-life model, lightning caused life on Earth: storms may have triggered reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the building blocks of life.
On Venus it's not like that: if there were ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and temperatures of 500°C reign on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
"Venus is possibly a 'diabolical' twin of Earth, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main goal of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth in mass and size, has evolved so differently.
As since the nineties there were no special missions, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the investigation of Venus.
The latest research results that will be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighbouring planets have more common features with Earth than we had assumed," reports ESA.
Despite the well-known stormy winds at the North Pole, researchers discovered in the south polar region also a vortex formed by clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the Earth's high atmospheric layers at the poles, according to a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has the mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet also called an alba star or evening star orbits the Sun for almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not closely resemble Earth, scientists assume that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets water had agglomerated that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
