According to Warhol, hundreds of glitter-cardboard boxes were exhibited at the 1968 exhibition of his 1968 works at the Musée Moderna Museet. These were not made by Warhol (because of the expense), but were brought directly from the cardboard factory of "Brillo".
These were not works of art, but specimens (which were only objects) exhibited.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed the production in Sweden of a glitter-wooden boxes, but they were not exhibited in the Modern Museum.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auction as originals of the "Brillo-Boxes" of "Stockholm type" authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auctions some of them were bought for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the museum Pontus Hultén made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But in reality, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Sultan and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had already died for 3 years.
Lars Byström, the chief curator of the Moderna Museet, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three privately owned by the Swedish that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. First their tight silvers were printed and frosted and then painted in oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the copies of the year 1990 shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the tight silvers. In addition, it is not about oil painting, but about acrylic paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol's official Brightness-Boxes list," says Lars Nittve, the director of the Moderna Museet museum, adding that if the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Commission in New York will not come to some conclusion, the Moderna Museet museum will classify these six boxes as the copies/exhibits."
Already in July the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these "serious accusations" in that they are boxes of soap powder.
But from that moment everything there remained in absolute silence.
Rebel soldiers surrender in Manila.
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers who had barricaded themselves in a hotel in Manila and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo have surrendered.
Ringleader Antonio Trillanes, who reproaches the president for corruption and electoral fraud, told a reporter he could not answer for bloodshed.
Soldiers loyal to the government had stormed the hotel using tear gas.
Almost two hundred soldiers had been barricading themselves in the building for a few hours.
Almost half of them, including Trillanes, were on trial Thursday for attempting a coup in 2003 that ended in failure.
He took advantage of the negotiations, to suddenly be able to deposit with about 30 supporters.
Evidently the military policemen who were supposed to watch him had passed into his ranks and continued his mutiny.
They entered the "Peninsula" hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Government troops blockaded the neighborhood around the Hotel Noble.
The president called for an urgent session of the Security Cabinet.
Norberto Gonzales, the national security adviser, condemned the soldiers' behavior.
"People are fed up," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join our ranks."
Gen. Danilo Lim, who formerly commanded the elite Scout Reangers, said the other military troops soon wanted to keep going.
The government's main critics called for a large demonstration against the president on Thursday.
For months his government has been reproached for corruption.
In 2003 the financial district in Manila was a site that attracted all the attention for the mutiny that was attempted against Arroyo.
The uprising failed after about 24 hours because the army wanted to participate.
Since 1986 in the Philippines there have been at least seven coup attempts against the democratically elected government.
United Internet will be Versatel's largest shareholder.
United Internet secured more than 20 percent of the shares of telecommunications company Versatel.
On Wednesday the company reported that the average price for a share is 14.46 euros.
It has only 20.05 percent of the share capital.
There was much speculation about the takeover of the company.
There are also options to further increase the financial part in Versatel.
United Internet reported that with this step it wants to accelerate the consolidation of the German DSL (Digital Subscriber Line) market.
On Wednesday they already made assumptions about entry into the business, after Brendenberg bank increased its stake to the Duesseldorf network operator by 5 percent to 15.1 percent.
In the financial market that means that the financial institution holds the equity securities for a third party partner.
United Internet already in the previous day involved with almost 10 percent to the telecommunications company Drillisch.
Drillisch in the measure of capital increase placed 17.4 million of the new shares that have a value of 106.4 million euros.
United Internet has bought 5.15 million shares of them for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies started negotiations on marketing cooperation for DSL-products.
"We strengthen our collaboration," explained the United Internet voice player.
The two companies founded a joint MSP company to acquire competitor Freenet.
On Thursday, United Internet reported that initially, the two companies want to be happy with the ten percent stake in Freenet and do not make use of their right, that is, they involve 18.49 percent of Freenet.
That meant that both companies kept all options, most notably the participation in the Freenet joint-stock company.
Negotiations between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership ended in mid-November.
This "game" with Freenet that will last for many months and is not very understandable is part of the consolidation of the German Telecom market.
At the end of the third quarter, Freenet had 2.9 million customers with a mobile phone contract and 1.27 million with a DSL contract or a full contract.
Until now, the holding company of United Internet and Drillisch directly held 6.01 percent of the stake in Freenet.
Then they had agreed that Drillisch will achieve the other four percent.
The right to buy 18.49 percent of the investment company Vatas was already agreed in August.
